PESTE DES PETITS RUMINANTS - ISRAEL: (HAZAFON) SHEEP, OIE
*********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 14 Apr 2021
Source: OIE, WAHID [edited]
https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=32054


Peste des petits ruminants, Israel
----------------------------------
General information
Report type: Immediate notification
Started: 2 Apr 2021
Confirmed: 4 Apr 2021
Reported: 14 Apr 2021
Reason for notification: Recurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 23 Aug 2020
Manifestation of disease: Clinical disease
Causal agent: Peste des petits ruminants virus
Nature of diagnosis: Clinical, laboratory
This event pertains to a zone of the country.

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks:
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Melea, Hazafon
Started: 3 Apr 2021
Epidemiological unit: Farm
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Sheep / 900 / 50 / 40 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: Some animals have been found with lesions on the muzzle.

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comments: The herd contains 900 animals: 600 ewes and approximately 300 lambs. The affected animals are young lambs.

Domestic control measures applied: Movement control inside the country, quarantine

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Kimron Veterinary Institute, Virology laboratory (national laboratory) / Sheep / Reverse transcription-polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) / 3-5 Apr 2021 / Positive

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The vaccination history of the flock has not been included in the report. In view of peste des petits ruminants (PPR) restricted to juveniles, it may be assumed -- while requiring confirmation -- that the adult animals have been vaccinated.

The fatality rate of 80% in susceptible lambs reflects the well-known pathogenicity potential of this disease.

A table presenting the number of PPR outbreaks affecting small ruminants (sheep and goats) in Israel between 1990 and 2019 is available on page 33 of the Veterinary Services' most recent annual report (2019) at https://www.moag.gov.il/vet/dochot-shnatiim/Documents/doch_shnati_2019.pdf. - Mod.AS

HealthMap/ProMED map:
Hazafon, Israel: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8311502,1759]
